      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-gray-900">Creating a Home Office on a Budget: Full Setup for Under $300</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-8 text-gray-600">
        You do not need thousands of dollars. Here is exactly how to put together a comfortable, ergonomic home office for under $300 total — with specific products, prices, and the reasoning behind each pick.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-10 prose prose-lg prose-gray max-w-none">

        <p>Most home office setup guides recommend $500 chairs, $600 desks, and $300 monitors — a $1,500+ total before you have even bought a lamp. That advice is not wrong — those products are genuinely better — but it is also not helpful if your budget is $300 total. This guide is for the version of me from six years ago: just starting out, not sure if remote work was even permanent, and definitely not able to spend a mortgage payment on office furniture.</p>

        <p>I built my first home office for about $280 in 2019 money. It was not beautiful. It was not impressive. But it was ergonomically sound — monitor at eye level, chair set to the right height, good task lighting — and it got me through two years of productive work while I saved up for better gear. Here is the 2026 version of that setup, with current prices and products.</p>

        <h2>The $300 Shopping List</h2>

        <h3>Desk: IKEA Lagkapten / Adils combo — $55</h3>

        <p>55 inches wide, 23.5 inches deep, available in white or wood-effect laminate. This is the desk equivalent of a reliable used car — not exciting, but it gets you where you need to go. The surface is honeycomb paper fill with a laminate coating, which means it is not real wood and will eventually show wear. But at $55, it is hard to complain.</p>

        <p>The 55-inch width gives you room for a monitor and a notebook side by side. The 23.5-inch depth is adequate — not generous, but adequate — for a monitor on a riser. Assembly takes about 20 minutes with the included tool. The legs have adjustable feet for uneven floors, which is a nice touch at this price.</p>

        <p><strong>Alternative:</strong> Check Facebook Marketplace for used desks. Office furniture depreciates hard — you can regularly find $200-400 desks for $40-80. Look for solid wood or metal-frame desks. Avoid anything with water damage, deep scratches through the surface, or a wobbly frame that cannot be tightened.</p>

        <h3>Chair: Hbada Office Task Chair — $130</h3>

        <p>I am putting the single largest chunk of the budget into the chair because this is where your body will thank you or hate you. The Hbada has adjustable lumbar support (height only, not depth, but at this price that is rare), a mesh back that actually breathes, and flip-up armrests. The foam seat is comfortable for an 8-hour day — not Aeron-level comfortable, but miles ahead of a dining chair.</p>

        <p>This is a 3-year chair, not a 10-year chair. The seat foam will start to soften noticeably around the two-year mark with daily use. But for $130, replacing it every three years is still cheaper over a decade than buying a $1,200 Aeron — and if you are on a tight budget, the cash flow matters more than the lifetime cost calculation.</p>

        <p><strong>Important:</strong> Take the time to actually adjust the lumbar support when you set it up. The knob on the back moves the support up and down. Find the position where you feel gentle pressure in the small of your back — that inward curve just above your belt line. An unadjusted ergonomic chair is barely better than an unadjusted dining chair.</p>

        <h3>Monitor: Used Dell 24-inch IPS — $50-80 (used)</h3>

        <p>This is where buying used makes the biggest difference. Office-grade monitors — Dell, HP, Lenovo — are built to run 8+ hours a day for years. Offices liquidate them by the pallet when they upgrade. You can find a perfectly functional 24-inch 1080p IPS Dell monitor on Facebook Marketplace or eBay for $50-80.</p>

        <p>Look for an IPS panel rather than TN — IPS has better color accuracy and wider viewing angles. Most Dell P-series and U-series monitors are IPS. Check that the stand adjusts for height (many Dell stands do, which eliminates the need for a separate monitor riser). Bring a laptop and an HDMI cable to test the monitor before buying — check for dead pixels, flickering, and damaged ports.</p>

        <p><strong>New alternative:</strong> Dell S2421H 24-inch ($110 new). IPS panel, thin bezels, built-in speakers adequate for video calls. If you cannot find a good used option or prefer the warranty of buying new, this is the budget pick.</p>

        <h3>Monitor riser: Bamboo stand — $20 (or a stack of books — free)</h3>

        <p>A simple bamboo or MDF monitor stand raises your screen so the top is at eye level. This is ergonomically non-negotiable — looking down at a laptop screen for hours is the fastest route to neck pain. If $20 breaks the budget, a stack of hardcover books works perfectly well. The books even add character.</p>

        <h3>Lighting: TaoTronics LED Desk Lamp — $30</h3>

        <p>Five brightness levels, five color temperatures (warm to daylight), a USB charging port on the base, and a flexible gooseneck. Over 20,000 Amazon reviews averaging 4.5 stars. The warm light settings (2700-3000K) are genuinely pleasant for evening work; the cooler settings (4000K) are better for daytime focus.</p>

        <p>A good desk lamp does more than illuminate your workspace — it reduces eye strain, makes you look better on video calls when positioned to light your face, and defines your "work zone" visually. The USB port on the base is a small but useful convenience for charging your phone without taking up an outlet.</p>

        <h3>Keyboard and mouse: Your laptop's, for now — $0</h3>

        <p>This is the one corner I am consciously cutting. If you are using a laptop on a riser, you will need an external keyboard and mouse — you cannot type comfortably on a laptop that is elevated to eye level. But for the initial setup, the absolute cheapest USB keyboard and mouse ($15-20 total) will work. Upgrade to something better when the budget allows. A Logitech K380 Bluetooth keyboard ($30) and M350 mouse ($20) are solid entry-level upgrades when you have another $50 to spend.</p>

        <h2>The math</h2>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto">
        <table>
          <tr><td>Desk (IKEA Lagkapten)</td><td>$55</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Chair (Hbada)</td><td>$130</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Monitor (used Dell 24")</td><td>$65 (used)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Monitor riser</td><td>$20</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Desk lamp</td><td>$30</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Keyboard + mouse (basic)</td><td>$15</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Total</strong></td><td><strong>$315</strong></td></tr>
        </table>
        </div>

        <p>Slightly over $300. Get the monitor riser for free (use books) and you are at $295. Buy the monitor used and you are comfortably within budget. Choose one or both adjustments depending on what you can find locally.</p>

        <h2>What to upgrade first when you have more money</h2>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>The chair ($180-500 range).</strong> This is always the first upgrade. A SIHOO M18 at $180-230 or a used Herman Miller Aeron at $400-600 will transform your daily comfort more than any other purchase. Your spine should be the first thing you upgrade.</li>
          <li><strong>A second monitor.</strong> Another used 24-inch Dell gives you the dual-monitor productivity boost for about $50-80. See our <a href="/blog/monitor-setup-guide/">monitor guide</a> for setup details.</li>
          <li><strong>A standing desk or converter ($250-300).</strong> Movement variety matters more than perfect posture. Sitting perfectly for eight hours is still worse than changing positions throughout the day. See our <a href="/blog/standing-desk-guide/">standing desk guide</a>.</li>
          <li><strong>A proper keyboard and mouse.</strong> A mechanical keyboard and an ergonomic mouse make typing and navigating more comfortable. Budget about $80-150 total when you are ready.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="rounded-2xl bg-accent-50 border border-accent-200 p-6 not-prose mt-10">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent-800">The most important thing is not the gear</p>
